Viewing file contents.

There are several tools for reading a file, and picking the right one for the job matters. The simplest is cat, short for concatenate, which prints a whole file straight to your terminal. That is fine for something small, a few dozen lines, but do not point it at a fifty-thousand-line log file or it will flood your screen. Given two files, cat prints them both, glued together, which is where its name comes from.

For anything large, reach for less, an interactive pager. Inside it you move with the space bar to go forward, the b key to go back, a slash to search, the n key for the next match, and q to quit. The clever thing about less is that it does not load the whole file into memory; it only reads the part you are currently looking at, so it can open a ten-gigabyte log instantly.

When you only want the ends of a file, head prints the first ten lines and tail prints the last ten, and both take a dash n flag to change that count. Tail has one killer feature: with the dash f flag, for follow, it keeps printing new lines as they are appended, which is the standard way to watch a log file live. There is also an older, simpler pager called more, but less is, by a deliberate pun, more than more, so just use less.

Finally there is the file command, which is not for reading a file but for identifying it. Linux does not trust file extensions, so file peeks at the first few bytes, the so-called magic number, and tells you what is really inside, whether that is an executable, plain text, or a p-n-g image.
